{"cursor":"8562","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nThe 'neutron detection temperature', also called the 'neutron energy', indicates\na free neutron's kinetic energy, usually given in electron volts. The term\ntemperature is used, since hot, thermal and cold neutrons are moderated in a\nmedium with a certain temperature. The neutron energy distribution is then\nadopted to the Maxwellian distribution known for thermal motion. Qualitatively,\nthe higher the temperature, the higher the kinetic energy is of the free\nneutron. Kinetic energy, speed and wavelength of the neutron are related through\nthe De Broglie relation.\n","linknr":268,"url":"Thermal_neutron","recorded":1362375449,"links":24,"instances":["statistics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Neutron","Temperature"],"headings":["Neutron energy distribution ranges","Fast reactor and thermal reactor compared","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Cold_Neutron_Source.jpg/350px-Cold_Neutron_Source.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf7/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/MaxwellBoltzmann-en.svg/350px-MaxwellBoltzmann-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf7/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["mode","statistics"],["mode","statistics"]],"members":["mode"],"related":["Free_neutron","Kinetic_energy","Electron_volt","Neutron_moderator","Maxwell–Boltzmann_distribution","Kinetic_energy","Speed","Wavelength","Matter_wave","Neutron_radiation","Neutron_moderator","